## How It Works

When a child process exits, the kernel sends SIGCHLD to the parent and marks the child as a zombie in the process table. The zombie persists until the parent collects the exit status with wait or waitpid. The process table entry is approximately 1.5 KB and includes the PID, exit code, user/kernel CPU time, memory usage, and termination signal.

Linux defaults to a PID maximum of 32768 (adjustable via /proc/sys/kernel/pid_max). Under load, each second of delay in reaping consumes one PID slot per exited child. At 1000 exits/second, 32768 zombies accumulate in ~33 seconds.

SIGCHLD is a standard signal and does not queue. If ten children exit before the signal handler runs, the handler receives exactly one SIGCHLD invocation. A single waitpid call inside that handler reaps exactly one child. The remaining nine stay zombie until the next SIGCHLD arrives or the next poll interval.

The WNOHANG flag makes waitpid non-blocking. The correct loop is:

```c
while ((pid = waitpid(-1, &status, WNOHANG)) > 0) {
    /* reap child */
}
```

A 30-second timer creates a worst-case zombie lifetime of 30 seconds and an average of 15 seconds. SIGCHLD-driven reaping drops lifetime to microseconds.

## Code Example

```c
#include <sys/wait.h>
#include <signal.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <errno.h>

volatile sig_atomic_t child_exited = 0;

void sigchld_handler(int sig) {
    child_exited = 1;
}

void reap_children(void) {
    while (1) {
        int status;
        pid_t pid = waitpid(-1, &status, WNOHANG);
        if (pid == 0) break;
        if (pid == -1 && errno == ECHILD) break;
        printf("Reaped PID %d exit %d\n", pid, WEXITSTATUS(status));
    }
}

int main() {
    struct sigaction sa = { .sa_handler = sigchld_handler, .sa_flags = SA_RESTART | SA_NOCLDSTOP };
    sigemptyset(&sa.sa_mask);
    sigaction(SIGCHLD, &sa, NULL);

    for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++) {
        if (fork() == 0) { sleep(1); _exit(0); }
    }

    // Reaping triggered by signal flag, not a timer
    while (1) {
        if (child_exited) {
            child_exited = 0;
            reap_children();
        }
        pause();
    }
    return 0;
}
```

Replace the timer-based polling with signal-flag-driven reaping. The volatile sig_atomic_t flag ensures no race in reading between main and the handler.

## Key Points

- **Signal coalescing**: Standard Unix signals do not queue. Multiple child exits produce one SIGCHLD delivery.
- **WNOHANG loop required**: A single waitpid inside a handler reaps only one child. Call in a loop until waitpid returns 0 or ECHILD.
- **Timer delay**: Every unit of reaping delay multiplies zombie accumulation by the exit rate.
- **pid_max limits**: Default 32768 PIDs. Container environments may lower this further via per-cgroup pids.max.
- **signalfd alternative**: On Linux, signalfd provides a file descriptor for signal events, enabling epoll-based reaping without signal handler context restrictions.

## Common Mistake

Calling wait or a single waitpid without WNOHANG inside the SIGCHLD handler. This reaps exactly one child per signal invocation. If ten children exit simultaneously, one is reaped and nine remain zombie until the next signal. The handler must loop on waitpid(-1, &status, WNOHANG) until it returns 0 (no more children) or -1 with errno ECHILD (no children remaining). Even experienced engineers write single-waitpid handlers.

Another frequent mistake is using SA_NOCLDWAIT as a shortcut. This flag causes the kernel to automatically reap children upon exit, but it discards the exit status entirely. If the parent needs exit codes for error reporting or health monitoring, SA_NOCLDWAIT is not usable.

## Interview Tip

The interviewer is listening for two specific insights. First, that SIGCHLD coalesces and a single waitpid call is insufficient under concurrency. Second, that timer-based polling creates a latency-vs-throughput tradeoff that produces burst zombies under load. The best answers also mention signalfd as a production-quality alternative that avoids signal handler restrictions entirely. The weakest answers describe zombies at the definition level without identifying the queueing failure mode or the WNOHANG loop pattern.
